DIV1.P: Mr. OGILBY's POCKET BOOK OF ROADS With the Computed & Measured Distances and the Distinction of Market and Post Townes
the Third Impression
To which is Added more Roads and Remarkable places omitted in the Former
Allsoe a Table for the Ready, finding any Road & the Distance from LONDON
By WILLIAM MORGAN His Majesty's Cosmographer
LONDON Printed for the Author and Sold at His House next the Blew Boar in Ludgate Street, And by the Seueral Booksellers In LONDON and Westminster &c 1679

DIV1.HEAD: ADUERTISMENT
DIV1.P: WILLIAM MORGAN having ocation to Print a 3d. Impression of this Book of Roads. To make it more Vseful and less Chargeable hath added Several Roads and Reduced the price to 8d. in sheets
The sheet MAP of England Being fitted to Bind with it, the Price 10d
Sold at his House Next the Blew Boar in Ludgate Street

P.HI: And Whereas Some late Proposers for Publishing an English Atlas; to Procure Subscribers. Doe falsly Pretend that Mr OGILBY'S design is Laied Aside &c
THIS is to Giue notice that Wm. MORGAN His Majesty's Cosmographer doth Prosecute & by Gods Asistance will finish Mr. OGILBY's Atlas;
Though he Doth not Publish any Proposalls Nor take Subscriptions Till he hath it in His Power to A sure the Adventurers When they shall Receive what they Subscribe for

DIV1.P: There hath been Already Layd out more then 7000 l. on the said work

DIV1.P: A Table of the Principal Townes and their distance from London &c.

The Numbers vnder C is the Computed distance vnder M.F. the measure by Miles and furlongs, for Example against Barwick vnder C.M.F. you have 262-339, 2 that is to say from London to Barwick is by Comput∣ation 262. miles by measure it is 339. miles and 2 Fur. The figure before the name directs you to fol: 2 where you have the Road to Barwick & the distance of each Town and soe of the Rest
A Table of the Cross Roads and the distance of the several Cities and Towns from those in Capitals
As from Bristol to Bath and all the Towns till you come to Brandon, then the following Towns take their distance from Brandon till you come to Bridgwater and soe of the Rest

DIV1.HEAD: EXPLANATION.
DIV1.P: IN each Road you have, 1st. named the Place whence, and to which the Road goeth, as Number 1. from London to Aberistwith, and in the Cross Roads, Cambridg to Coventry, &c. then follows the Names and perticular Distance of each Remarkable Place you pass.
The Numbers under C. shews you the Vulgar Computation, the Numbers under M. F. gives you the Measured Di∣stance by Miles and Furlongs.

And by casting up the Numbers you have the distance of any one Town from another as fol 1. No 1. from London to Stoken-church you will find it by compu∣tation 35 miles & by Measure 39 mile 2 furl of which 8. makes a mile, & so of the Rest.
But we haue given you the Totalls of the Computation and Measure of each Road with the Cities and Market Townes thereon, in the foregoing Tables

Where the Computation is omitted or that Town is not a mile from the Next admits of some odd parts, of a Mile & in such cases we have given the Com∣puted Distance from the Town before to the Town following the Omittion.

As in the Roads to Aberistwith, from Kensington Gravel-pits to Shepheards-Bush, it is by Measure 1. Mile 7. Furl∣longs but the Computation is omitted till you come to Acton, which is ac∣counted 3. miles from Kensington Gra∣vel-pits.
We have Devided the Roads under Two Heads, Roads from London, and Cross Roads.

In the Roads from London there are divers that go part of the Way, and then turn out of the great Roads; & to avoid Repeating the Towns and their Distances, till you come to the place where you leave the great Road, you are Referred to the Read out of which each Branch Issues.

As in the Road from London to Buck∣ingham you are directed to Number 1. for the Way as far as Uxbridg, and in the Road from London to Montgomery, you are Referred to Number 1. for the Way as far as Worcester, where the Road to Aberistwith and the Road to Montgomery part, and so of the Rest.

The Cross Roads are such as Lead from one City or great Town to ano∣ther, and have no Repetition or Re∣ference: they are placed Alphabetical∣ly where the Town that begins the Road takes place, as the Town that ends the Road doth in those from London, but the Tables direct you readily to find either.

For Distinction Cities are in CA∣PITALS, Market-Towns in Italique, and Post-Towns markt thus * as Page 1. * Waltham-Cross is a Post and not a Market-Town, Hodsdon is a Market and not a Post-Town, * Ware is both Market and Post, &c.
